# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emetine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] In aqueous solution 8-hydroxyquinoline has a pKa value of ca.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] 9.9 It reacts with metal ions, losing the proton and forming 8-hydroxyquinolinato-chelate complexes.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] The aluminium complex, is a common component of organic light-emitting diodes (OLEDs).
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] Substituents on the quinoline ring affect the luminescence properties.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] In its photo-induced excited-state, 8-hydroxyquinoline converts to zwitterionic isomers, in which the hydrogen atom is transferred from oxygen to nitrogen.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] 8-hydroxyquinoline was first obtained by Hugo Weidel and his student Albert Cobenzl in 1880.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] They decarboxylated so-called oxycinchoninic acid (from cinchonine) and characterized the resulting compound as melting at about 70°C.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] They identified that the hydroxy group is on the benzene ring (but not its particular place) and called the compound **oxyquinoline** and **α-quinophenol**.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] In the following year more chemists found other ways to make the compound.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] Zdenko Hans Skraup discovered a way to synthesize substituted quinolines from substituted phenols and described three isomers of oxyquinoline, identifying the structure of 8-hydroxyquinoline.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] Otto Fischer and his student Karl Bedall made the compound from a sulphonic acid independently at about the same time, but misidentified its structure.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] By 1888 azo dyes were made from the compound.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] In the 1920s insoluble chelates of 8-hydroxyquinoline were discovered.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] The complexes as well as the heterocycle itself exhibit antiseptic, disinfectant, and pesticide properties, functioning as a transcription inhibitor.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] Its solution in alcohol is used in liquid bandages.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] It once was of interest as an anti-cancer drug.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] A thiol analogue, 8-mercaptoquinoline is also known.
[src:emetine/8-hydroxyquinoline] The roots of the invasive plant *Centaurea diffusa* release 8-hydroxyquinoline, which has a negative effect on plants that have not co-evolved with it.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Infection of the cornea by *Acanthamoeba* is difficult to treat with conventional medications, and AK may cause permanent visual impairment or blindness, due to damage to the cornea or through damage to other structures important to vision.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Recently, AK has been recognized as an orphan disease and a funded project, Orphan Drug for Acanthamoeba Keratitis (ODAK), has tested the effects of a diverse range drugs and biocides on AK.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In the United States, *Acanthamoeba* keratitis is nearly always associated with soft contact lens use.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] *Acanthamoeba* spp. is most commonly introduced to the eye by contact lenses that have been exposed to the organism through the use of contaminated lens solution, using homemade saline-based solution or tap water, or from wearing contact lenses while bathing or swimming.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, it may also be introduced to the eye by exposure to soil or vegetation, or by trauma.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In fact, the first case of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis described was due to ocular trauma.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Once on the contact lens, *Acanthamoeba* is able to survive in the space between the contact lens and the surface of the eye.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Soft contact lenses are more adherent to the corneal surface than hard lenses, which allows the *Acanthamoeba* organism to bind to mannosylated glycoproteins on the corneal surface.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Expression of these proteins on the corneal surface is increased by contact lens use.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] This increase in glycoprotein content, along with microtrauma to the corneal epithelial surface due to contact lens use increases the risk for infection.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Once the organism has gained access to the surface of the eye, it is able to invade through the epithelium and Bowman's layer.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In some cases, the infection can then group around corneal nerves, producing radial deposits (radial keratoneuritis), and causing extreme pain.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] These are features also seen in viral and bacterial keratitis, and may be misleading.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The organism is also capable of invading deeper into the cornea; using metalloproteases it is able to penetrate deep into the stroma of the cornea.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] As the disease progresses, it may penetrate through the cornea but very rarely causes infection inside the eye (endophthalmitis) due to a robust neutrophil response in the anterior chamber.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] While the vast majority of cases of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis occur in contact lens wearers, there have been many cases of *Acanthamoeba* described in those who do not wear contact lenses, especially outside the United States.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In non-contact lens users, the greatest risks for developing *Acanthamoeba* infection are trauma and exposure to contaminated water.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Further predisposing factors include contaminated home water supply, and low socioeconomic status.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Infection is also more commonly seen in tropical or sub-tropical climates.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Beyond the route of inoculation into the eye and external risk factors, host factors are also likely to play a significant role in the development of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In fact, studies of contact lens users in the United Kingdom, Japan, and New Zealand found that 400 to 800 per 10,000 asymptomatic contact lens users had lens storage cases contaminated with *Acanthamoeba* spp.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, the rate of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis among these patients was only 0.01 to 1.49 per 10,000 contact lens users.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Although the exact host factors have not been fully described, it is likely that corneal epithelial defects, tear film composition, eye surface pH, and the level of anti-*Acanthamoeba* IgA antibodies in the tear film play a role in the development of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Species within the genus, *Acanthamoeba*, are generally free-living trophozoites.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] These trophozoites are relatively ubiquitous and can live in, but are not restricted to, tap water, freshwater lakes, rivers and soil.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In addition to the trophozoite stage, the organism can also form a double-walled cyst which may also be present in the environment, and can be very difficult to eradicate through medical treatment.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Both of these stages are usually non-nucleated and reproduce by the means of binary fission.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Due to the relative rarity of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis (AK) compared to other causes of keratitis (bacterial, viral, etc.), it is often misdiagnosed, especially in the early stages of the disease.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] AK should be considered in all patients who use contact lenses, and following corneal abrasions or trauma.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A thorough history should be obtained, especially relating to contact lens use and any recent changes in contact lens solution, exposure of the eyes to water or foreign objects, and symptoms that the patient is experiencing.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The symptoms classically attributed to AK include decreased or blurred vision, sensitivity to light (photophobia), redness of the eye (conjunctival hyperemia), and pain out of proportion to physical exam findings.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Another clinical feature that can distinguish *Acanthamoeba* from bacterial causes of keratitis is a lack of discharge from the eye.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] On physical exam, findings will depend on the stage of the disease.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Early manifestations in the cornea can be seen as punctate keratopathy, pseudodendrites, and epithelial or subepithelial corneal deposits.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] These features can lead an examiner to confuse AK with a viral keratitis, such as that caused by varicella zoster virus or herpes simplex virus.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] As the disease progresses and infiltrates the corneal stroma, a classic "ring infiltrate" may be present on examination (although this is only seen in about 50% of cases).
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Corneal ulceration, or in severe cases, perforation, can also occur and may be accompanied by hypopyon.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In cases of keratitis, diagnosis is typically achieved through evaluation of corneal scrapings.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Scrapings are taking from the cornea, and plated on agar for culture, and also can be stained using Gram stain and Giemsa stain to differentiate between bacterial keratitis and AK.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] To culture *Acanthamoeba,* scrapings are placed on a non-nutrient agar saline plate seeded with a gram-negative bacteria such as *E. coli*.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] If *Acanthamoeba* are present, they will reproduce readily and become visible on the plate under 10–20 times objective on an inverted microscope.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Polymerase chain reaction (PCR) can be used to confirm a diagnosis of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis, especially when contact lenses are not involved.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Confocal microscopy is a non-invasive technique that allows visualization of *Acanthamoeba in vivo* in cases in which corneal scraping, culture, and cytology do not yield a diagnosis.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Once *Acanthamoeba* keratitis is diagnosed, initiation of timely and appropriate treatment will have a significant impact on visual outcomes.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Medical therapy aims to eradicate both trophozoite and cystic forms of *Acanthamoeba* and also control the inflammatory response.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Multiple classes of drugs have been found to be effective in killing the trophozoite form of *Acanthamoeba*, including anti-bacterial, anti-fungal, anti-protozoal, and anti-neoplastic agents.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, no single therapy has been found to eliminate both trophozoite and cystic forms, and to eradicate corneal infection.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] One class of medications used in treatment is the biguanides, which include polyhexamethylene biguanide (PHMB) 0.02% to 0.06% drops, and chlorhexidine 0.02 to 0.2% drops.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] These medications disrupt the cell wall of the trophozoite organism, leading to its death.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, these agents have shown limited efficacy against the cystic forms.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Due to the efficacy of these drugs against the *Acanthamoeba,* as well as their low toxicity to the cornea, they are commonly used as the first line medications in the treatment of AK.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Biguanides have also been found to act synergistically when used in combination with diamidines, with propamidine isethionate and hexamidine being the most commonly used.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A limitation of diamidine use is relative corneal toxicity with long term use.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A combined regimen of propamidine, miconazole nitrate, and neomycin has also been suggested.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Due to the potential for negative longterm visual outcomes with AK, therapy is usually started with a combination of a biguanide and a diamidine.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Early use of high dose dual therapy helps to eliminate both trophozoite and cyst forms of the organism, while also preventing deep penetration of cysts into the corneal stroma.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Cysts that are not eradicated from the cornea will cause recurrence.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The treatment is often initiated by instilling drops onto the surface of the eye every hour, 24 hours a day, for at least the first 48–72 hours.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] If an appropriate response to therapy, this may be reduced to hourly administrations during the day only, which is continued for several weeks to months.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Beyond anti-amoebic therapies, there is also a role for topical steroids of anti-inflammatory medications in the treatment of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] During infection, severe inflammation in the cornea and anterior chamber can cause more severe symptoms including pain and visual disturbance.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Topical steroids may be used to reduce this inflammation and thereby alleviate symptoms.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] However, the role of steroids is typically very limited, because their dampening of the immune response may lead to worsening of the infection.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Additionally, steroids can increase the number of trophozoites in the cornea by inducing excystation.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Therefore it is typically recommended that steroids be used briefly to aid in symptom resolution, and that anti-amoebic agents be used both during, and for several weeks after topical steroid use.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Surgical debridement of an infected cornea can also be used to reduce organism load and excise devitalized tissue from the cornea.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] It may also improve the efficacy of medical therapy by promoting penetration of medication into deeper layers of the cornea.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] In cases of corneal ulceration or perforation, or if corneal scarring is severe, corneal transplant may be required.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] This typically involves full thickness transplantation of the cornea from a healthy donor eye.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The size of the graft should be kept as small as possible, as larger grafts carry a great risk of host rejection, and due to the possibility of graft revision surgery.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] While surgery is capable of restoring vision by replacing a damaged cornea, it also carries risks of recurrent *Acanthamoeba* infection or graft failure.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] For this reason, anti-amoebic medications should be started prior to surgery, and continued for several weeks afterward.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] If there is suspicion or evidence of recurrent infection, cultures should be sent.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] If cultures are positive, anti-amoebic therapy should be continued for 6 months.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] Outcomes following surgery are typically much better for patients who receive surgery for vision improvement following infection resolution, and therefore all efforts should be made to maximize medical management before attempting surgery.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A study in Austria reported a total of 154 cases of *Acanthamoeba* keratitis over a 20-year period.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The age of those with AK ranged from 8 to 82 years old and 58% of the people were female.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] The data showed that 89% of the infected patients were contact lens wearers, almost all cases occurred only in one eye, and 19% required a corneal transplant.
[src:emetine/acanthamoeba-keratitis] A study in 2023 calculated the incidence of acanthamoeba keratitis to be approximately 2.9 cases per million people.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Alkaloids are produced by a large variety of organisms including bacteria, fungi, plants, and animals.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] They can be purified from crude extracts of these organisms by acid-base extraction, or solvent extractions followed by silica-gel column chromatography.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Many have found use in traditional or modern medicine, or as starting points for drug discovery.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Other alkaloids possess psychotropic (e.g. psilocin) and stimulant activities (e.g. cocaine, caffeine, nicotine, theobromine), and have been used in entheogenic rituals or as recreational drugs.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Alkaloids can be toxic (e.g. atropine, tubocurarine).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Although alkaloids act on a diversity of metabolic systems in humans and other animals, they almost uniformly evoke a bitter taste.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The boundary between alkaloids and other nitrogen-containing natural compounds is not clear-cut.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Most alkaloids are basic, although some have neutral and even weakly acidic properties.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] In addition to carbon, hydrogen and nitrogen, alkaloids may also contain oxygen or sulfur.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Rarer still, they may contain elements such as phosphorus, chlorine, and bromine.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Compounds like amino acid peptides, proteins, nucleotides, nucleic acid, amines, and antibiotics are usually not called alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Natural compounds containing nitrogen in the exocyclic position (mescaline, serotonin, dopamine, etc.) are usually classified as amines rather than as alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Some authors, however, consider alkaloids a special case of amines.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The name "alkaloids" (German: *Alkaloide*) was introduced in 1819 by German chemist Carl Friedrich Wilhelm Meissner, and is derived from late Latin root *alkali* and the Greek-language suffix -οειδής -('like').
[src:emetine/alkaloid] However, the term came into wide use only after the publication of a review article, by Oscar Jacobsen in the chemical dictionary of Albert Ladenburg in the 1880s.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The name "alkaloid" was introduced, since at the time, chemists conceptualized the category of "alkaline" in such a way that plants cannot produce alkaline.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] For instance, potash, an alkaline substance that can be extracted from plants by burning, was thought to be either produced during burning, or extracted by plant from the soil.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Subsequent research by chemists to extract the "principle" (what we nowadays call the active ingredient) of medicinal plants, led to the discovery of various substances that had properties resembling alkalines as understood at the time.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] These substances were variously named "salifiable vegetable bases", "vegetable organic compounds", "organic bases", etc.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] After enough such substances were discovered, these substances were classified as "alkaloid", a new chemical category.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] There is no unique method for naming alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Many individual names are formed by adding the suffix "ine" to the species or genus name.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] For example, atropine is isolated from the plant *Atropa belladonna*; strychnine is obtained from the seed of the Strychnine tree (*Strychnos nux-vomica* L.).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Where several alkaloids are extracted from one plant their names are often distinguished by variations in the suffix: "idine", "anine", "aline", "inine" etc.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] There are also at least 86 alkaloids whose names contain the root "vin" because they are extracted from *vinca* plants such as *Vinca rosea* (*Catharanthus roseus*); these are called *vinca* alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Alkaloid-containing plants have been used by humans since ancient times for therapeutic and recreational purposes.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] For example, medicinal plants have been known in Mesopotamia from about 2000 BC.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The *Odyssey* of Homer referred to a gift given to Helen by the Egyptian queen, a drug bringing oblivion.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] It is believed that the gift was an opium-containing drug.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] A Chinese book on houseplants written in 1st–3rd centuries BC mentioned a medical use of ephedra and opium poppies.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Also, coca leaves have been used by Indigenous South Americans since ancient times.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Extracts from plants containing toxic alkaloids, such as aconitine and tubocurarine, were used since antiquity for poisoning arrows.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Studies of alkaloids began in the 19th century.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] In 1804, the German chemist Friedrich Sertürner isolated from opium a "soporific principle" (Latin: *principium somniferum*), which he called "morphium", referring to Morpheus, the Greek god of dreams; in German and some other Central-European languages, this is still the name of the drug.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The term "morphine", used in English and French, was given by the French physicist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] A significant contribution to the chemistry of alkaloids in the early years of its development was made by the French researchers Pierre Joseph Pelletier and Joseph Bienaimé Caventou, who discovered quinine (1820) and strychnine (1818).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Several other alkaloids were discovered around that time, including xanthine (1817), atropine (1819), caffeine (1820), coniine (1827), nicotine (1828), colchicine (1833), sparteine (1851), and cocaine (1860).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The development of the chemistry of alkaloids was accelerated by the emergence of spectroscopic and chromatographic methods in the 20th century, so that by 2008 more than 12,000 alkaloids had been identified.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The first complete synthesis of an alkaloid was achieved in 1886 by the German chemist Albert Ladenburg.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] He produced coniine by reacting 2-methylpyridine with acetaldehyde and reducing the resulting 2-propenyl pyridine with sodium.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Compared with most other classes of natural compounds, alkaloids are characterized by a great structural diversity.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Initially, when knowledge of chemical structures was lacking, botanical classification of the source plants was relied on.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] This classification is now considered obsolete.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] More recent classifications are based on similarity of the carbon skeleton (*e.g.*, indole-, isoquinoline-, and pyridine-like) or biochemical precursor (ornithine, lysine, tyrosine, tryptophan, etc.).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] However, they require compromises in borderline cases; for example, nicotine contains a pyridine fragment from nicotinamide and a pyrrolidine part from ornithine and therefore can be assigned to both classes.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] "Protoalkaloids", which contain nitrogen (but not the nitrogen heterocycle) and also originate from amino acids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Examples include mescaline, adrenaline and ephedrine.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Polyamine alkaloids – derivatives of putrescine, spermidine, and spermine.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Pseudoalkaloids – alkaloid-like compounds that do not originate from amino acids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] This group includes terpene-like and steroid-like alkaloids, as well as purine-like alkaloids such as caffeine, theobromine, theacrine and theophylline.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Some authors classify ephedrine and cathinone as pseudoalkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Those originate from the amino acid phenylalanine, but acquire their nitrogen atom not from the amino acid but through transamination.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Some alkaloids do not have the carbon skeleton characteristic of their group.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] So, galanthamine and homoaporphines do not contain isoquinoline fragment, but are, in general, attributed to isoquinoline alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Most alkaloids contain oxygen in their molecular structure; those compounds are usually colorless crystals at ambient conditions.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Oxygen-free alkaloids, such as nicotine or coniine, are typically volatile, colorless, oily liquids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Some alkaloids are colored, like berberine (yellow) and sanguinarine (orange).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Most alkaloids are weak bases, but some, such as theobromine and theophylline, are amphoteric.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Many alkaloids dissolve poorly in water but readily dissolve in organic solvents, such as diethyl ether, chloroform or 1,2-dichloroethane.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Caffeine, cocaine, codeine and nicotine are slightly soluble in water (with a solubility of ≥1g/L), whereas others, including morphine and yohimbine are very slightly water-soluble (0.1–1 g/L).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Alkaloids and acids form salts of various strengths.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] These salts are usually freely soluble in water and ethanol and poorly soluble in most organic solvents.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Exceptions include scopolamine hydrobromide, which is soluble in organic solvents, and the water-soluble quinine sulfate.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Most alkaloids have a bitter taste or are poisonous when ingested.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Alkaloid production in plants appeared to have evolved in response to feeding by herbivorous animals; however, some animals have evolved the ability to detoxify alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Some alkaloids can produce developmental defects in the offspring of animals that consume but cannot detoxify the alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] One example is the alkaloid cyclopamine, produced in the leaves of corn lily.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] During the 1950s, up to 25% of lambs born by sheep that had grazed on corn lily had serious facial deformations.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] These ranged from deformed jaws to cyclopia.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] After decades of research, in the 1980s, the compound responsible for these deformities was identified as the alkaloid 11-deoxyjervine, later renamed to cyclopamine.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Alkaloids are generated by various living organisms, especially by higher plants – about 10 to 25% of those contain alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Therefore, in the past the term "alkaloid" was associated with plants.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The alkaloids content in plants is usually within a few percent and is inhomogeneous over the plant tissues.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Depending on the type of plants, the maximum concentration is observed in the leaves (for example, black henbane), fruits or seeds (Strychnine tree), root (*Rauvolfia serpentina*) or bark (cinchona).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Furthermore, different tissues of the same plants may contain different alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Beside plants, alkaloids are found in certain types of fungus, such as psilocybin in the fruiting bodies of the genus *Psilocybe*, and in animals, such as bufotenin in the skin of some toads and a number of insects, markedly ants.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Many marine organisms also contain alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Some amines, such as adrenaline and serotonin, which play an important role in higher animals, are similar to alkaloids in their structure and biosynthesis and are sometimes called alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Because of the structural diversity of alkaloids, there is no single method of their extraction from natural raw materials.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Most methods exploit the property of most alkaloids to be soluble in organic solvents but not in water, and the opposite tendency of their salts.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Their mixture is extracted first and then individual alkaloids are separated.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Plants are thoroughly ground before extraction.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Most alkaloids are present in the raw plants in the form of salts of organic acids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The extracted alkaloids may remain salts or change into bases.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Base extraction is achieved by processing the raw material with alkaline solutions and extracting the alkaloid bases with organic solvents, such as 1,2-dichloroethane, chloroform, diethyl ether or benzene.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Then, the impurities are dissolved by weak acids; this converts alkaloid bases into salts that are washed away with water.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] If necessary, an aqueous solution of alkaloid salts is again made alkaline and treated with an organic solvent.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The process is repeated until the desired purity is achieved.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] In the acidic extraction, the raw plant material is processed by a weak acidic solution (*e.g.*, acetic acid in water, ethanol, or methanol).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] A base is then added to convert alkaloids to basic forms that are extracted with organic solvent (if the extraction was performed with alcohol, it is removed first, and the remainder is dissolved in water).
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The solution is purified as described above.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Alkaloids are separated from their mixture using their different solubility in certain solvents and different reactivity with certain reagents or by distillation.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] A number of alkaloids are identified from insects, among which the fire ant venom alkaloids known as solenopsins have received greater attention from researchers.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] These insect alkaloids can be efficiently extracted by solvent immersion of live fire ants or by centrifugation of live ants followed by silica-gel chromatography purification.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Tracking and dosing the extracted solenopsin ant alkaloids has been described as possible based on their absorbance peak around 232 nanometers.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Biological precursors of most alkaloids are amino acids, such as ornithine, lysine, phenylalanine, tyrosine, tryptophan, histidine, aspartic acid, and anthranilic acid.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Nicotinic acid can be synthesized from tryptophan or aspartic acid.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Ways of alkaloid biosynthesis are too numerous and cannot be easily classified.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] However, there are a few typical reactions involved in the biosynthesis of various classes of alkaloids, including synthesis of Schiff bases and Mannich reaction.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Schiff bases can be obtained by reacting amines with ketones or aldehydes.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] These reactions are a common method of producing C=N bonds.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] An integral component of the Mannich reaction, in addition to an amine and a carbonyl compound, is a carbanion, which plays the role of the nucleophile in the nucleophilic addition to the ion formed by the reaction of the amine and the carbonyl.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] In addition to the described above monomeric alkaloids, there are also dimeric, and even trimeric and tetrameric alkaloids formed upon condensation of two, three, and four monomeric alkaloids.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] There are also dimeric alkaloids formed from two distinct monomers, such as the *vinca* alkaloids vinblastine and vincristine, which are formed from the coupling of catharanthine and vindoline.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] The newer semi-synthetic chemotherapeutic agent vinorelbine is used in the treatment of non-small-cell lung cancer.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] It is another derivative dimer of vindoline and catharanthine and is synthesised from anhydrovinblastine, starting either from leurosine or the monomers themselves.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Alkaloids are among the most important and best-known secondary metabolites, i.e. biogenic substances not directly involved in the normal growth, development, or reproduction of the organism.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Instead, they generally mediate ecological interactions, which may produce a selective advantage for the organism by increasing its survivability or fecundity.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] In some cases their function, if any, remains unclear.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] An early hypothesis, that alkaloids are the final products of nitrogen metabolism in plants, as urea and uric acid are in mammals, was refuted by the finding that their concentration fluctuates rather than steadily increasing.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Most of the known functions of alkaloids are related to protection.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] For example, aporphine alkaloid liriodenine produced by the tulip tree protects it from parasitic mushrooms.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] In addition, the presence of alkaloids in the plant prevents insects and chordate animals from eating it.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] However, some animals are adapted to alkaloids and even use them in their own metabolism.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Such alkaloid-related substances as serotonin, dopamine and histamine are important neurotransmitters in animals.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Alkaloids are also known to regulate plant growth.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] One example of an organism that uses alkaloids for protection is the *Utetheisa ornatrix*, more commonly known as the ornate moth.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Pyrrolizidine alkaloids render these larvae and adult moths unpalatable to many of their natural enemies like coccinelid beetles, green lacewings, insectivorous hemiptera and insectivorous bats.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Another example of alkaloids being utilized occurs in the poison hemlock moth (*Agonopterix alstroemeriana).* This moth feeds on its highly toxic and alkaloid-rich host plant poison hemlock (*Conium maculatum*) during its larval stage.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] *A. alstroemeriana* may benefit twofold from the toxicity of the naturally occurring alkaloids, both through the unpalatability of the species to predators and through the ability of *A. alstroemeriana* to recognize *Conium maculatum* as the correct location for oviposition.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] A fire ant venom alkaloid known as solenopsin has been demonstrated to protect queens of invasive fire ants during the foundation of new nests, thus playing a central role in the spread of this pest ant species around the world.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Medical use of alkaloid-containing plants has a long history, and, thus, when the first alkaloids were isolated in the 19th century, they immediately found application in clinical practice.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Many synthetic and semisynthetic drugs are structural modifications of the alkaloids, which were designed to enhance or change the primary effect of the drug and reduce unwanted side-effects.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] For example, naloxone, an opioid receptor antagonist, is a derivative of thebaine that is present in opium.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Prior to the development of a wide range of relatively low-toxic synthetic pesticides, some alkaloids, such as salts of nicotine and anabasine, were used as insecticides.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Their use was limited by their high toxicity to humans.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Preparations of plants and fungi containing alkaloids and their extracts, and later pure alkaloids, have long been used as psychoactive substances.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Cocaine, caffeine, and cathinone are stimulants of the central nervous system.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Mescaline and many indole alkaloids (such as psilocybin, dimethyltryptamine and ibogaine) have hallucinogenic effect.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Morphine and codeine are strong narcotic pain killers.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] There are alkaloids that do not have strong psychoactive effect themselves, but are precursors for semi-synthetic psychoactive drugs.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] For example, ephedrine and pseudoephedrine are used to produce methcathinone and methamphetamine.
[src:emetine/alkaloid] Thebaine is used in the synthesis of many painkillers such as oxycodone.
[src:emetine/amebicide] An **amebicide** (or **amoebicide**) is an agent that is destructive to amoeba, especially parasitic amoeba that cause amoebiasis.
[src:emetine/amebicide] Metronidazole, or a related drug such as tinidazole, secnidazole or ornidazole, is used to destroy amoebae that have invaded tissue.
[src:emetine/amebicide] These are rapidly absorbed into the bloodstream and transported to the site of infection.
[src:emetine/amebicide] Because they are rapidly absorbed there is almost none remaining in the intestine.
[src:emetine/amebicide] Doses for children are calculated by body weight and a pharmacist should be consulted for help.
[src:emetine/amebicide] Since most of the amoebae remain in the intestine when tissue invasion occurs, it is important to get rid of those also or the patient will be at risk of developing another case of invasive disease.
[src:emetine/amebicide] Several drugs are available for treating intestinal infections, the most effective of which has been shown to be paromomycin (also known as Humatin); iodoquinol (also known as Yodoxin) is used in the US; and diloxanide furoate (also known as Furamide) is used in certain other countries.
[src:emetine/amebicide] Propamidine isethionate has been used in the treatment of Acanthamoeba infection.
[src:emetine/amebicide] The Nicobarese people have attested to the medicinal properties found in *Glochidion calocarpum*, a plant endemic to India, saying that its bark and seed are most effective in curing abdominal disorders associated with amoebiasis.
[src:emetine/amebicide] Although *Naegleria* is sometimes considered amoeboid, unlike Acanthamoeba or Balamuthia it is not closely related to the Amoebozoa (it is much more closely related to *Leishmania*) and agents used to treat *Naegleria* infections are usually addressed separately.
[src:emetine/american-society-of-health-system-pharmacists] The aim of the society is to support the professional practice of pharmacists in hospitals and health systems.
[src:emetine/american-society-of-health-system-pharmacists] In addition, the society advocates to government agencies, such as the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) on public policy issues related to medication use and public health.
[src:emetine/atc-code-p01] National versions of the ATC classification may include additional codes not present in this list, which follows the WHO version.
[src:emetine/emetine] Mechanism of action of emetine was studied by François Magendie during the nineteenth century.
[src:emetine/emetine] Early use of emetine was in the form of oral administration of the extract of ipecac root, or ipecacuanha.
[src:emetine/emetine] This extract was originally thought to contain only one alkaloid, emetine, but was found to contain several, including cephaeline, psychotrine and others.
[src:emetine/emetine] Although this therapy was reportedly successful, the extract caused vomiting in many patients, which reduced its utility.
[src:emetine/emetine] In some cases, it was given with opioids to reduce nausea.
[src:emetine/emetine] Other approaches to reduce nausea involved coated tablets, allowing the drug to be released after digestion in the stomach.
[src:emetine/emetine] The identification of emetine as more potent than ipecac extract improved the treatment of amoebiasis.
[src:emetine/emetine] While use of emetine still caused nausea, it was more effective than the crude extract of ipecac root.
[src:emetine/emetine] Additionally, emetine could be administered hypodermically which still produced nausea, but not to the degree experienced in oral administration.
[src:emetine/emetine] Although it is a potent antiprotozoal, the drug also can interfere with muscle contractions, leading to cardiac failure in some cases.
[src:emetine/emetine] Because of this, in some uses it is required to be administered in a hospital so that adverse events can be addressed.
[src:emetine/emetine] Dehydroemetine is a synthetically produced antiprotozoal agent similar to emetine in its anti-amoebic properties and structure (they differ only in a double bond next to the ethyl group), but it produces fewer side effects.
[src:emetine/emetine] Cephaeline is a desmethyl analog of emetine also found in ipecac root.
[src:emetine/emetine] Emetine dihydrochloro hydrate is used in the laboratory to block protein synthesis in eukaryotic cells.
[src:emetine/emetine] It does this by binding to the 40S subunit of the ribosome.
[src:emetine/emetine] This can thus be used in the study of protein degradation in cells.
[src:emetine/emetine] Mutants resistant to emetine are altered in the 40S ribosomal subunit (S14 protein), and they exhibit cross-resistance to cryptopleurine, tylocrebrine, cephaeline and tubulosine, but not other inhibitors of protein synthesis.
[src:emetine/emetine] The compounds to which these mutants exhibit cross-resistance have been shown to share common structural determinants with emetine that are responsible for their biological activities.
[src:emetine/emetine] The biosynthesis of cephaeline and emetine come from two main biosynthesis pathways: the biosynthesis of dopamine from L-tyrosine and the biosynthesis of secologanin from geranyl diphosphate.
[src:emetine/emetine] Biosynthesis begins from a Pictet-Spengler reaction of dopamine and secologanin forming N-deacetylisoipecoside (S-form) and N-deacetylipecoside (R-form).
[src:emetine/emetine] The S-form then goes through a series of reactions including O-methylations, deglucosylation and reduction to form protoemetine.
[src:emetine/emetine] Protoemetine then reacts with another dopamine molecule to form 7'-O-demethylcephaeline.
[src:emetine/emetine] The final products are then produced with a 7'-O-methylation to make cephaeline and a 6'-O-methylation successively to make emetine.
[src:emetine/emetine] Heavy or overusage of emetine can carry the risk of developing proximal myopathy and/or cardiomyopathy.
[src:emetine/emetine] A 2018 study at Princeton University and Thomas Jefferson University has demonstrated that emetine blocks the dissemination of rabies virus inside nerve cells, but the exact mechanism is still under investigation.
[src:emetine/emetine] Emetine had no effect on the transport of endosomes devoid of the rabies virus.
[src:emetine/emetine] But endosomes carrying the virus were either completely immobilized, or were only able to move short distances at slower-than-normal speeds.
[src:emetine/emetine] In 2016, a study found that low doses of emetine inhibited cytomegalovirus replication and was synergistic with ganciclovir.
